s, and she considers how various interventions carried a lasting influence. The advent of the workhouse, the denigration of the nonworking poor as "social parasites," efforts to police homelessness and vagrancy--all had significant impact on the lives of people struggling to survive. Chen provides a crucially needed historical lens for understanding how beliefs about poverty intersected with shattering historical events, producing new welfare policies and institutions for the benefit of some, but to the detriment of others. Drawing on vast archival material, Guilty of Indigence deepens the historical perspective on poverty in China and reveals critical lessons about a still-pervasive social issue.Some images inside the book are unavailable due to digital copyright restrictions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aPovertyxGovernment policyzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPovertyzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aUrban poorzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aBeijing.  aChina.  aCommunists.  aJapanese penology.  aNanjing Decade.  aNationalist Party.  aNationalist government.  aPeople's Republic.  aRepublican-era China.  aShanghai.  aWorld War II.  aagrarian revolutionaries.  abeggars.  acitizenship.  acoffin repositories.  acustodial detention.  adetention.  agovernment custody.  agovernment institutions.  ahomelessness.  aincarceration.  aindustrial training.  alabor.  anonworking poor.  apoor relief.  apoorhouses.  apoverty policies.  aproductive citizens.  aproductivism.  areforming elites.  arefugee crisis.  arefugees.  arelief agencies.  arelief agenda.  ascientific charity.  asecurity.  ashantytowns.  asocial dislocation.  asocial parasites.  asocialist ideology.  asociology.  astraw huts.  atwent